#范文[The charts illustrate three aspects of Little Chalfont Library’s usage in 2016 and borrowing trends between 2007 and 2016.

Overall, adults aged 18–64 constituted the majority of library members, and fiction—both adult and children’s—accounted for the largest share of loans. Additionally, total book loans showed a general upward trajectory over the ten-year period.

In 2016, 51% of library members were adults between 18 and 64 years old, making this the largest demographic group. Children under 13 represented 22% of members, followed by teenagers (aged 13–17) at 15%, while those aged 65 and over formed the smallest group at 12%.

Regarding borrowing preferences, fiction was overwhelmingly popular across age groups. Specifically, adult fiction and children’s fiction each accounted for 38% of all loans. Adult non-fiction made up a much smaller proportion (13%), while adult audio books and children’s DVDs represented only 2% and 1% respectively. Notably, children’s borrowing activity was disproportionately high relative to their membership share, whereas teenagers borrowed far less than their membership percentage would suggest.

From 2007 to 2016, total loans rose from just over 15,000 to approximately 22,000. Despite a slight dip between 2011 and 2013, the overall trend was clearly upward, with the highest number of loans recorded in the final year.]

